definition.value: A drug used for its effects on the gastrointestinal system, e.g. controlling gastric acidity, regulating gastrointestinal motility and water flow, and improving digestion.
An imidazolidine containing one or more oxo groups.
Oxazoles in which the N and O atoms are adjacent.
Compounds containing a cyclic dicarboximide skeleton in which the two carboacyl groups on nitrogen together with the nitrogen itself form a 1H-pyrrole-2,5-dione structure.
A carboxamide consisting of L-homoserine lactone having an unspecified N-acyl substituent.
A compound having the general formula RR'C(OH)OR'' (R'' =/= H).
A cyclic compound having as ring members atoms of at least two different elements.
Tetraanion of coenzyme A.
An acyl-CoA(4-) that is the tetraanion of acetyl-CoA, arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups.
A ribonucleoside triphosphate oxoanion that is the trianion of adenosine 5'-triphosphate arising from deprotonation of three of the four free triphosphate OH groups.
An amino acid zwitterion arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of glycine.
Tetraanion of phenylacetyl-CoA arising from deprotonation of phosphate and diphosphate functions.
Zwitterionic form of D-alanine.
Trianion of UTP arising from deprotonation of three of the OH groups from the triphosphate moiety.
Dianion of N-acetyl-D-glucosamine 6-phosphate arising from deprotonation of both OH groups of the phosphate.
A fatty acid anion with a chain length of C13 or greater.
Conjugate base of biotin arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
An organophosphate oxoanion that is the dianion of sn-glycerol 3-phosphate arising from deprotonation of both phosphate OH groups.
Dianion of N-acyl-D-glucosamine 6-phosphate arising from deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups.
Trianion of GTP arising from deprotonation of three of the four phosphate OH groups.
Zwitterionic form of gamma-amino-beta-hydroxybutyric acid having an anionic carboxy group and a protonated amino group.
A carboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any N-acylglycine.
A glycerol 1-phosphate(2-) that is the dianion of sn-glycerol 1-phosphate arising from deprotonation of both phosphate OH groups.
Conjugate base of quercetin arising from selective deprotonation of the 7-hydroxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of D-tryptophan having an anionic carboxy group and a protonated alpha-amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A D-alpha-amino acid zwitterion that is D-threonine in which a proton has been transferred from the carboxy group to the amino group. It is the major species at pH 7.3.
An ammonium ion that is the trication of spermidine, formed by protonation at all three nitrogens.
Zwitterionic form of L-methionine having a anionic carboxy group and a cationic amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
Dianion of L-fuculose 1-phosphate arising from deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups; major species at pH 7.3.
A nucleoside 5'-monophosphate(2-) that results from the removal of two protons from the phosphate group of UMP.
The conjugate base of a nucleoside 5'-phosphate.
Zwitterionic form of 6-aminopenicillanic acid arising from migration of a proton from the carboxy group to the 6-amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
An L-alpha-amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of L-tryptophan; major species at pH 7.3.
A peptide anion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups and protonation of the glutamyl amino group of glutathione; major species at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of L-threonine arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
Trianion of nucleoside diiphosphate arising from deprotonation of all three free OH groups of the diphosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of D-methionine arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of beta-alanine arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
An ammonium ion that is the trication of hygromycin B arising from protonation of the three amino groups; major species at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of L-alanine arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate base of 2-dehydro-3-deoxy-D-gluconic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate acid of a primary aliphatic amine.
Trication of streptomycin arising from protonation of the guanidino and secondary amino groups.
Zwitterionic form of anhydrotetracycline arising from transfer of a proton from the 2-hydroxy to the tertiary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
The dianion of a nucleoside monophosphate: major species at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of L-asparagine arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
An amino acid zwitterion of homocysteine arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate acid of homoserine lactone; major species at pH 7.3.
Trianion of nucleoside triphosphate arising from deprotonation of three of the four free triphosphate OH groups; major species at pH 7.3.
An organophosphate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of 3',5'-cyclic AMP arising from deprotonation of the free phosphate OH group; major species at pH 7.3.
